<p>

<b>Charles Hatchett</b> (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../788/15788.xml">
2 January</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../870/34870.xml">
1765</link> - <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../196/20196.xml">
10 March</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../954/34954.xml">
1847</link><ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref>) was an <link>
English</link> chemist who discovered the element <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../275/21275.xml">
niobium</link>.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref></p>

<sec>
<st>
 Life </st>

<p>

Hatchett was born, raised, and lived in London.  On 24 March 1787, he married Elizabeth Collick at St Martin's-in-the-Fields, with issue including:
<list>
<entry level="1" type="number">

John Charles Hatchett (bapt 27 Jan 1788 St Martin's-in-the-Fields)</entry>
<entry level="1" type="number">

Anna Hatchett, who married William Brande</entry>
</list>
</p>
<p>

Hatchett died in London and is buried at <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../737/4306737.xml">
St Laurence's Church, Upton, Slough</link>, the same church where <scientist wordnetid="110560637" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../971/33971.xml">
William Herschel</link></scientist>
 is buried.</p>

</sec>
<sec>
<st>
Columbite</st>

<p>

In 1801 while working for the <museum wordnetid="103800563" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../675/4675.xml">
British Museum</link></museum>
 in <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../867/17867.xml">
London</link></village>
, Hatchett analyzed a piece of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../324/506324.xml">
columbite</link> in the museum's collection.  Columbite turned out to be a very complex <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../053/19053.xml">
mineral</link>, and Hachett discovered that it contained a "new earth" which implied the existence of a new element.  Hatchett called this new element columbium (Cb).  On <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../581/21581.xml">
26 November</link> of that year he announced his discovery before the <body wordnetid="107965085" confidence="0.8">
<social_group wordnetid="107950920" confidence="0.8">
<association wordnetid="108049401" confidence="0.8">
<club wordnetid="108227214" confidence="0.8">
<group wordnetid="100031264" confidence="0.8">
<administration wordnetid="108164585" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../064/496064.xml">
Royal Society</link></administration>
</group>
</club>
</association>
</social_group>
</body>
.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%223%22])">3</ref><ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%224%22])">4</ref>  The element was later rediscovered and renamed niobium (its current name).  </p>
<p>

Later in life, Hatchett quit his job as a chemist to work full time in his family's coach fabrication business.</p>

</sec>
<sec>
<st>
Award</st>

<p>

Since 1979, the Institute of Materials (London) has given the Charles Hatchett Award yearly to a noted chemist. The award is given to the "author of the best paper on the science and technology of niobium and its alloys."</p>

